(json 159 (comment_id "652"))
(json 159 (user_id "51"))
(json 159 (proposal_id "4675"))
(json 159 (content "Hello Gombilla, thank you for your comments and encouragment! I agree that ethical considerations are of paramount importance here. Certainly they should be with any project asking for personal information. Where disabilities are concerned, the sense of vulnerability to exploitation is especially heightened. For autistic people, just disclosing our condition affects our employment options and can lead to layoffs. It has for me. For our project, there's no need for personal information to be shared, but we would need to understand skills, traits and accommodations requests for sensitivities like bright lights or noise to build the job matching model. I favour firstly the EU's privacy protections and the right to be forgotten in digital records. This is a step in the right direction. I also favour Wishknish's especially strong security, but that is ahead of us as an enterprise-level solution. For this start to our project, the LOET, my approach is to share anonymized data with permission from the user, and we'll communicate this much more clearly than is usual for conventional apps. A part of the service we'd like to perform for the neurodivergent community is a clearer sense of skills and needs across genders, ethnicities and cultures. Neurodivergent characteristics are relatively under-studied in this more wholistic inclusive sense. So to summarize, as I am one of the neurodivergent individuals affected by this situation, we must build up our own models, trained by us in the ND community, while also, and seriously, protecting privacy. Then we can be leaders develoaping solutions to help us. I'm grateful there are people like yourself who care about these questions and articulate them so well."))
(json 159 (comment_votes "0"))
(json 159 (created_at "2024-06-07 03:10:53"))
(json 159 (updated_at "2024-06-07 03:10:53"))
